pr_body:
I want to remove the ``cliquet.http_scheme`` for the following reasons:

* Tests did not break when I took it out (*untested code does not exist.*)
* It is *cliquet* specific, and gives the impression that we do some magic with it, whereas WSGI and Pyramid already manage this stuff
* It is unclear whether changing requests attributes will truely override Pyramid internal machinery on URLs (which partly relies on WSGI environs)

I suggest we had some documentation and highlight pitfalls of WSGI apps proxifying instead... such as for Nginx: 

```
        proxy_set_header        Host $http_host;
        proxy_set_header        X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header        X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header        X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
```

No longer needed since gRPC works (mostly?) everywhere.

---

@tseaver I stopped short of combining `REQUIREMENTS` and `GRPC_EXTRAS` in `setup.py` but it seems like that is do-able now. WDYT?

... and run `flake8` in all files.

@BibMartin easy review and merge.

I am skipping Python 3.3 not because it is failing, but it is a well know distribution for problems and people are recommended to upgrade. By skipping it in our Travis-CI we only get faster results.

It turned out that Google Protobuf will use the proto file name as a key to register ProtoDescription upon initialization. Therefore all the string replacing tricks are not enough to avoid conflict when we load two version of onnx into one process. The solution here is to rename the proto file itself and create a proxy "onnx.pb.h" header file so that downstream files won't need to change their include all together. 

It fixes the cmake as well as the setup.py. I think it's time that we try to call cmake inside setup.py to avoid duplicated effort. 

@dzhulgakov Do you have any suggestion on maybe a better way of including onnx as static lib?
